WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:16.440
In the last few modules, we've talked about all the different components that we have within

00:16.440 --> 00:17.440
a system.

00:17.440 --> 00:33.040
Now let's talk about some of the significant vulnerabilities.

00:33.040 --> 00:36.280
In the last few modules, we've talked about all the different components that we have

00:36.280 --> 00:37.600
within a system.

00:37.600 --> 00:47.360
Now let's talk about some of the significant vulnerabilities that we have in systems.

00:47.360 --> 00:52.240
So here's a list of some of the major architectural risks that exist in systems, things like single

00:52.240 --> 00:55.200
points of failures and bypass controls and race conditions.

00:55.200 --> 00:58.880
We'll go through each of these and we'll talk about what the risk is or what the vulnerability

00:58.880 --> 01:04.200
is and in most cases how you would go about mitigating that vulnerability.

01:04.200 --> 01:07.760
Let's start with this concept of a single point of failure.

01:07.760 --> 01:10.320
So what is a single point of failure?

01:10.320 --> 01:14.560
Well a single point of failure is where you've got a single system or process that if it

01:14.560 --> 01:17.160
goes down, everything goes down.

01:17.160 --> 01:20.920
So in this little diagram that we have here, we've got the sketchy internet at the very

01:20.920 --> 01:22.120
top there.

01:22.120 --> 01:26.160
We've got the traffic coming in from the internet going through a firewall and then through

01:26.160 --> 01:31.120
a router down to our little happy systems in our trusted internal network.

01:31.120 --> 01:32.120
You don't have a trusted network.

01:32.120 --> 01:33.920
We'll talk with that later.

01:33.920 --> 01:37.520
So what are the single points of failure in this diagram here?

01:37.520 --> 01:39.280
Well there's two.

01:39.280 --> 01:43.800
Our firewall and our router are both single points of failure.

01:43.800 --> 01:47.760
So how do we address the risks of single points of failure?

01:47.760 --> 01:53.800
Well, it's through redundancy or having multiple systems and in this diagram here you can

01:53.800 --> 01:56.640
see we don't just have one firewall and one router.

01:56.640 --> 02:01.840
We have two firewalls and two routers and we have them interconnected.

02:01.840 --> 02:07.080
So if one router goes down or one firewall goes down, the traffic is just routed around.

02:07.080 --> 02:10.600
So that's how we reduce the risk of single points of failure.

02:11.080 --> 02:14.560
Next, let's talk about bypass controls.

02:14.560 --> 02:18.480
Now before I explain exactly what a bypass control is, let me tell you a story and I think

02:18.480 --> 02:20.200
this will all make sense, okay?

02:20.200 --> 02:24.760
So let's say I'm a network administrator and I've just bought some wicked new firewall.

02:24.760 --> 02:29.520
It's like a million dollar firewall and being the very security conscious network administrator

02:29.520 --> 02:30.520
that I am.

02:30.520 --> 02:34.920
When this firewall gets delivered in the morning, I type in as my first task, I type in

02:34.920 --> 02:39.840
some super strong 50 character password for the root account so that it's a very secure

02:39.840 --> 02:42.560
firewall and you know, that was a big job.

02:42.560 --> 02:47.320
So I go off and have lunch and then I come back from lunch and I type in the super secure

02:47.320 --> 02:51.360
50 character password and correct password, crap.

02:51.360 --> 02:58.200
I type it in again, I type it in another time, oh, I've just forgotten the password to

02:58.200 --> 03:00.360
the million dollar firewall.

03:00.360 --> 03:01.360
What do I do now?

03:01.360 --> 03:04.480
Do I take the million dollar firewall and just throw it in the garbage because I mean,

03:04.480 --> 03:07.560
this is the root account without access to this account.

03:07.560 --> 03:09.800
You can't configure this firewall.

03:09.800 --> 03:10.800
So what do you do?

03:10.800 --> 03:15.960
Well, you get out a paperclip, you bend it open and walk up to the back of the firewall,

03:15.960 --> 03:20.240
find a little pinhole in the back, hold the paperclip in there for about 10 seconds and

03:20.240 --> 03:21.640
what happens?

03:21.640 --> 03:24.240
The firewall configuration resets.

03:24.240 --> 03:27.440
This is a perfect example of a bypass control.

03:27.440 --> 03:31.600
So in the diagram that I'm showing you here, our regular control is that a user would

03:31.600 --> 03:35.000
log into a system with a password.

03:35.000 --> 03:37.880
But let's say the user has forgotten their password.

03:37.880 --> 03:41.600
We want to implement a bypass control.

03:41.600 --> 03:47.880
So bypass controls are controls that we intentionally build into a system to allow us to bypass some

03:47.880 --> 03:51.000
primary mechanism, like say the authentication mechanism.

03:51.000 --> 03:54.840
So we very clear on this wording, bypass controls are intentional.

03:54.840 --> 03:57.800
They're intentionally built into a system.

03:57.800 --> 03:59.800
Do they introduce additional risks?

03:59.800 --> 04:00.800
Of course they do.

04:00.800 --> 04:04.080
And this example that I just gave you with the million dollar firewall, if someone was

04:04.080 --> 04:08.800
able to get physical access to that firewall, they could reset the firewall.

04:08.800 --> 04:12.440
And there are lots and lots of examples of bypass controls out there.

04:12.440 --> 04:17.760
And all of them, whenever you implement a bypass control, it introduces additional risk.

04:17.760 --> 04:21.120
So how do we reduce the risk of bypass controls?

04:21.120 --> 04:25.160
Well, you've got to implement the appropriate mitigating controls, whatever those happen

04:25.160 --> 04:26.160
to be.

04:26.160 --> 04:29.680
In the example of a firewall, it would be physical security.

04:29.680 --> 04:33.880
As long as you prevent someone an unauthorized person from getting physical access to the

04:33.880 --> 04:36.920
firewall, they can't reset the firewall.

04:36.920 --> 04:40.680
So whatever is the appropriate mitigating control, you put that in place to reduce the

04:40.680 --> 04:45.320
risk of any new risk you've implemented with a bypass control.

04:45.320 --> 04:51.200
And now let's talk about these six letters here, TOC, TOU, TalkTow.

04:51.200 --> 04:52.200
What do they stand for?

04:52.200 --> 04:58.400
Well, TOC, time of check and TOU, time of use.

04:58.400 --> 05:01.600
What this refers to is often also referred to as a race condition.

05:01.600 --> 05:04.200
And let me tell you another story to explain this one.

05:04.200 --> 05:09.840
So let's say I walk into work in the morning, I get my laptop out, plug it in, and type

05:09.840 --> 05:12.480
in my username and password and log into the system.

05:12.480 --> 05:16.800
And just as I log in, someone from HR comes and says, Rob, kind of please see you in my

05:16.800 --> 05:17.800
office.

05:17.800 --> 05:19.000
And I say, yeah, sure, no problem.

05:19.000 --> 05:23.720
We walk right over to their office, and they sit me down and say, and they say, Rob,

05:23.720 --> 05:26.480
you're a terrible employee, we're firing you.

05:26.480 --> 05:31.040
And I think my response would probably be like, yeah, I get it, I'm a pretty horrible

05:31.040 --> 05:32.040
person.

05:32.040 --> 05:33.040
I'm on the same page.

05:33.040 --> 05:34.040
I get it.

05:34.040 --> 05:35.040
No worries.

05:35.040 --> 05:36.320
So it's a very quick discussion.

05:36.320 --> 05:41.480
And I leave to the HR person's office, and I'm back at my desk in like three minutes.

05:41.480 --> 05:43.720
What do I find when I'm back at my desk?

05:43.720 --> 05:48.600
Well, I may well find that my laptop is still logged in.

05:48.600 --> 05:53.040
My screensaver might not be set to time out for, say, five minutes.

05:53.040 --> 05:57.800
So if I'm back at my laptop, and I'm able to access that laptop, should I be able to?

05:57.800 --> 05:58.800
And of course not.

05:58.800 --> 06:00.200
I've just been fired.

06:00.200 --> 06:04.560
This is a perfect example of time of check, time of use, or a race condition.

06:04.560 --> 06:10.120
The idea is if an attacker can race in and get access to and use a system before there's

06:10.120 --> 06:14.400
the next check, they might be able to do something that they're not supposed to.

06:14.400 --> 06:17.320
They might be able to hijack the session as an example.

06:17.320 --> 06:23.000
So how do we reduce the risk of time of check, time of use, or race conditions?

06:23.000 --> 06:26.120
Well, you have to increase the frequency of reauthentication.

06:26.120 --> 06:29.880
So in the example I gave of coming back to my laptop, if the screensaver password had

06:29.880 --> 06:34.320
come up after even just one minute, then I wouldn't have had unauthorized access to

06:34.320 --> 06:35.320
that system.

06:35.320 --> 06:40.520
So the way we do deal with the risk of time of check, time of use is increase the frequency

06:40.520 --> 06:44.240
of reauthentication.

06:44.240 --> 06:47.000
The next vulnerability we're going to talk about is emanations.

06:47.000 --> 06:48.880
Now let's start with an definition.

06:48.880 --> 06:50.600
What does emanations mean?

06:50.600 --> 06:54.280
Well, computer systems emanate all sorts of different stuff.

06:54.280 --> 06:56.480
They emanate light from the screen.

06:56.480 --> 06:58.200
They emanate sounds.

06:58.200 --> 07:02.360
They emanate radio waves and some of them are intentional, things like our Wi-Fi.

07:02.360 --> 07:05.880
Our magnetic hard drives when they're being used emanate magnetic waves.

07:05.880 --> 07:10.120
There's all sorts of stuff that our systems emanate.

07:10.120 --> 07:16.000
And the risk with emanations is that someone may be able to detect those emanations and

07:16.000 --> 07:21.200
gather information that they're not supposed to from those emanations.

07:21.200 --> 07:26.040
Now there's three major ways that we can deal with the risk of emanations.

07:26.040 --> 07:28.400
The first is shielding.

07:28.400 --> 07:35.160
So what this means is you put some sort of shield around the device that blocks electromagnetic

07:35.160 --> 07:36.480
waves.

07:36.480 --> 07:39.480
An example of shielding is something known as tempest.

07:39.480 --> 07:40.640
And you should remember this.

07:40.640 --> 07:47.000
So tempest is a tech suite of technologies developed by the Royal Military to protect their

07:47.000 --> 07:52.440
planes and tanks and things like that from the rescues or whomever, from the bad guys

07:52.440 --> 07:54.320
whoever those happen to be.

07:54.320 --> 08:00.320
So one of the ways that we prevent reduce the risk of emanations is shielding.

08:00.320 --> 08:03.000
The next is white noise.

08:03.000 --> 08:04.800
What is white noise?

08:04.800 --> 08:06.840
Static random noise.

08:06.840 --> 08:10.920
And the idea behind white noise is that if you blast a really strong signal of random

08:10.920 --> 08:16.520
noise, whatever small weak emanations might be coming out of your system will be overwhelmed

08:16.520 --> 08:21.000
by the random noise, preventing the attacker from listening in and gathering data from

08:21.000 --> 08:23.240
your system.

08:23.240 --> 08:27.720
The final major way that we can deal with the risk of emanations is what are known as control

08:27.720 --> 08:28.720
zones.

08:28.720 --> 08:30.720
Think of this as physical security.

08:30.720 --> 08:35.080
Control zones simply means that if someone isn't able to get close enough to your system

08:35.080 --> 08:39.840
that's emanating these weak signals, then they're not going to be able to pick them up.

08:39.840 --> 08:44.640
And so this is why in the movies, the super security government system is always buried

08:44.640 --> 08:47.640
in some bunker underground inside of a mountain.

08:47.640 --> 08:51.520
And the only way to get through getting near it is to hire Tom Cruise to repel out of

08:51.520 --> 08:53.600
the vents in the ceiling or something like that.

08:53.600 --> 08:58.400
So control zones, control physical access to the device to reduce the risk of emanations.

